05991nam a2200757Ia 9781501733147DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20191993nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017331477 a10.7591/97815017331472doi  a(DE-B1597)534603  a(OCoLC)1178770078  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0230002bisacsh04a338.952qOCoLC220/eng/2023021600aPolitical Dynamics in Contemporary Japan /ced. by Gary D. Allinson, Yasunori Sone. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b8 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tTables and Figures -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Analyzing Political Change: Topics, Findings, and Implications -- tPART ONE. STRUCTURAL FEATURES OF JAPAN'S DYNAMIC POLITY -- tIntroduction -- t1. Citizenship, Fragmentation, and the Negotiated Polity -- t2. Patterned Pluralism under Challenge: The Policies of the 1980s -- t3. State Strength and the Public Interest -- tPART TWO. NEGOTIATING FINANCIAL REFORM -- tIntroduction -- t4. Financial Deregulation and Interest Intermediation -- t5. Deregulation and Legalization of Financial Policy -- tPART THREE. NEGOTIATING LABOR'S ROLE -- tIntroduction -- t6. A Tale of Twin Industries: Labor Accommodation in the Private Sector -- t7. Public Sector Labor and the Privatization Challenge: The Railway and Telecommunications Unions -- t8. Rengo and Its Osmotic Networks -- tPART FOUR. SITES AND MODES OF NEGOTIATION -- tIntroduction -- t9. Of Fairy Cloaks and Familiar Talks: The Politics of Consultation -- t10. The Rise and Retreat of a Neoliberal Reform: Controversies over Land Use Policy -- t11. Privatizing Regulation: The Implementation of the Large-Scale Retail Stores Law -- tConclusion: Structuring Political Bargains: Government, Gyokai, and Markets -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRising affluence, social fragmentation, and international participation have wrought subtle but important changes in Japanese politics. Political resources have expanded, political coalitions have become more fluid, and political disputes have become more vigorously contested. In this book six American and six Japanese specialists join to identify and interpret these changes. They start from the administrative reform movement of the 1980s, which magnified the significance of contests over public and private interests.Several of the authors examine domestic issues profoundly shaped by the reform movement: deregulation of financial services, privatization and its consequences, reorganization within the labor movement, negotiation of land use polices, and regulation of retail trade. Others adopt a broader perspective to illuminate the nation's shifting policy agenda, the changing role of the state and its relation to public interests, and the historical and socioeconomic context of political change. An approach that acknowledges the pervasiveness and importance of continuous bargaining, they maintain, promises to enhance our understanding of the domestic politics of contemporary Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh1 aAllinson, Gary D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllinson, Gary D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKume, Ikuo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMabuchi, Masaru, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCall Rosenbluth, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKean, Marga